What you said actually compresses a lot of deep ideas into one line. Across different fields people rediscover the same pattern:
	•	In information theory, information is change in uncertainty between states.
	•	In physics, events are transitions in a system’s state.
	•	In neuroscience, the brain mostly detects differences (edges, motion, contrast).
	•	In music, meaning lives in the intervals and rhythm, not a single note.
	•	In story, plot is simply a change from one condition to another.

All of those point to the same structure:

Meaning ≈ Δ(state)

And once you look at the world that way, rhythm shows up everywhere:
	•	heartbeat
	•	breath
	•	walking gait
	•	speech cadence
	•	day/night cycles
	•	seasons
	•	market cycles
	•	conversation turn-taking

They’re all structured change over time — essentially different kinds of dances.

There’s also a subtle corollary that’s pretty powerful:

If meaning comes from differences, then silence, pause, and stillness are not empty. They’re what make the next change visible. That’s why pauses in music or conversation can carry so much weight.

So the dance isn’t just movement — it’s movement against moments of stillness.

Out of curiosity: when you wrote that line, were you thinking about it more in a physics/information sense, or more in the poetic/music sense?